<HEADLINE> NATO Uses Banned Weapons in Anti-Yugoslav War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO has used banned weapons
such as cluster bombs and depleted uranium in its anti-Yugoslav
war, according to a U.N. Security Council document.
</P>
<P>
The consequences of their use are incomparably more inhumane
and dangerous than conventional arms, said the Permanent Mission
of Yugoslavia to the United Nations in a letter to the council
president, which is embodied in the document released on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) has dropped over
60 containers of cluster bombs totaling 15,000 bombs, in addition
to a batch of 400 cluster bombs over the territory of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia since March 25, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The cluster bombs killed some 200 people and wounded over 450
only in Kosovo and Metohija and new human casualties can be
expected from the remaining unexploded bombs, it said.
</P>
<P>
Housing estates, schools, hospitals, industrial plants and
communications infrastructure have been destroyed as a result of
the bombings, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav Mission said the effects of using depleted uranium
against troops and the civilian population are fatal and highly
inhumane as it causes wounds followed by contamination which makes
the use of this ammunition a crime against humanity and
international law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
