<HEADLINE> Canada's Cost of Living Jumps in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation jumped in
April to 1.7 percent from 1.0 percent in March, the largest annual
increase since October 1997, Statistic Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Roughly one third of the increase was due to higher costs for
transportation, reflecting higher prices for gasoline, new cars
and trucks, and air fares.
</P>
<P>
The price index for gasoline rose 5.9% since April 1998. The
increase can be explained by a higher demand for gasoline, a
tightening of North American supply and the recent agreement by
OPEC countries to lower production of crude oil, said the federal
agency.
</P>
<P>
The increase represented the first year-over-year advance in
the price of gasoline since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Fuel oil prices were up 6.8 percent last month, also due to
higher world prices for fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
Higher home costs, especially the price of natural gas and
property taxes, also contributed to the rise in April costs, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Before Friday's report, the inflation rate had been fluctuating
between 0.6 percent and one percent since November 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
