<HEADLINE> U.S. Vietnam War Veteran Strives for Peace in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Ron Kovic, a Vietnam War
veteran, called Thursday for an immediate cessation of the NATO
bombing on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Kovic, who was paralyzed during the Vietnam war and has been in
wheelchair for 30 years, said the United States has become one of
the most dangerous roadblocks to the peace of the world.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that our country has taken us to a dangerous and
reckless path," he said. "We are deeply concerned."
</P>
<P>
Kovic Wednesday traveled 3000 miles from Los Angeles to the
Chinese embassy in the United States to express his condolences
for the three journalists killed on NATO's attack on the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade on May 7.
</P>
<P>
Kovic said the U.S. government must make a "sincere and formal"
apology to China for the missile attack on the Chinese embassy.
</P>
<P>
"The President must not just shrug his shoulder and say we are
sorry," he said, "there must be a change of this awful and
terrible behavior, there must be a true apology."
</P>
<P>
"They must learn to say sorry and truly change their hearts,"
said Kovic, who was alos an artist and author of the non-fiction
"Born on the Fourth of July", which was made into a famous motion
picture in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Kovic, who said he spoke for millions of peace-minded
Americans, stressed that he would do everything possible to stop
the "terrible" bombing on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"I am an American citizen, but I am also a citizen of the
world," he said,"to be a good American in 1999 means to honor and
respect people from other places and other cultures, and to build
bridges of friendship rather than continue a policy of
aggression."
</P>
<P>
"I hope someday the voices of peace can be louder than all the
bombings by NATO," said the war veteran turned peace-maker.
</P>
<P>
Kovic said he was strongly opposed to the U.S. policy which
were on many occasions "unconscionable and immoral", whether it
was relating to Vietnam, Iraq or Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The war veteran said he was arrested several times simply
because of trying to speak against his government's policy,
which was "deeply immoral and in many cases barbaric".
</P>
<P>
"This terrible policy will only cause tension in the world,"
he said, "we must move away from war."
</P>
<P>
"I deeply wish for peace, and our destiny is to live in peace
and become brothers and sisters." he added.
</P>
<P>
Kovic said he would like to visit Belgrade as a peace-maker to
show that Americans want the bombing to never happen again.
</P>
<P>
Though this is not an easy journey for a person in wheelchair,
he said he was not afraid to go for the sake of peace.
</P>
<P>
"I have been to the wars, this is not a place I want to return
to, but for peace I want, for a peaceful world in the next century
I would take risks."
</P>
<P>
"A journey of one thousand miles begins with the first step",
he said, citing an old Chinese saying.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like to be a peace maker and work together
with more than one billion Chinese people for world peace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
