<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Determine Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- African countries have been urged to
 undertake action leading to debt cancellation and determine their
 own development path.
</P>
<P>
The three-day regional conference of "Toward an African
Consensus on Sustainable Solutions to the Debt Problem" concluded
here Friday by adopting the Lusaka Declaration.
</P>
<P>
"Our conference is part of a process of movement-building
within and beyond Africa: a movement against the crippling impact
of debt on billions of people across the world, and for a new,
people-centered genuine form of development," the declaration
said.
</P>
<P>
African countries reiterated the call for total debt
cancellation, and insist that creditors and G7 countries cannot be
allowed to dictate the terms of cancellation, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Highly Indebted Poor Country (HIPC) initiative put forward
by the International Monetary Fund and other debt relief
proposals, including the recent proposals from G7 countries,
notably from the United States, Britain and Germany, all insist on
unacceptable conditions, and entail inadequate amounts of relief,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it added, the so-called debt relief initiatives have
not resulted from inclusive negotiations. The Paris Club and the
HIPC initiative are merely processes and frameworks imposed by
creditors on debtors.
</P>
<P>
"We reject HIPC and the other current debt relief processes and
commit ourselves to expose their fundamental flaws in each of the
countries, particularly in the run-up to the June G8 Meeting in
Cologne, Germany," the declaration said, adding "as members of
African civil society, we believe we have the standing to speak
truth to power, in the presence of overwhelming Northern financial
arrogance".
</P>
<P>
In short, debt is one of the most important instruments of the
North domination over the South, and the domination of financiers
over people, production and nature everywhere, it noted.
</P>
<P>
"As part of our struggle to liberate ourselves from this
bondage, we make demands for the cancellation of debt as part of a
broader struggle to fundamentally transform the current world
economic order and transfer power from the political leadership of
the rich countries, " said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we commit ourselves to working against localized
symptoms of our debt burden and economic process, including war,
corruption and other evils that undermine our development
process," it said.
</P>
<P>
The organizer of the conference, an anti-debt campaign, the
Jubilee 2000 Group, which is part of the world-wide movement
lobbying the donor countries and the international financial
institutions to cancel the debt of poor countries by the year
2000, said it wants to collect about 22 million signatures at next
month's meeting of G7/8, and press the leaders to consider
canceling the debt of the Third World countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
