<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends Iraq Oil-For-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Friday adopted a resolution under which the U.N.
oil-for-food program in Iraq will remain for another six months.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution unanimously adopted, Iraq is allowed to
sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil in this period.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the Security Council requested the U.N.
Secretary-General to report to it if Iraq is unable to export
petroleum and petroleum products sufficient to the total sum and
make recommendations for the expenditure of the sum expected to be
available.
</P>
<P>
Iraq complained to the United Nations early this week that the
oil-for-food program was useless and the only way to alleviate
the suffering of the Iraqi people was lifting the sanctions
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under stringent U.N. sanctions since its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990. The oil-for-food program, which began in
December 1996, is designed to offset the impact of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The current phase of oil-for-food program will expire next
Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
