<HEADLINE> S. Leone Fighting Continues Amid Impending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting continued Thursday in
Sierra Leone before a hardly-earned truce could take effect next
Monday, the country's state radio confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
The west Africa peacekeeping force or ECOMOG had come under
severe attack by rebel forces in the country's eastern town of
Kenema, an important diamond-producing area, and Port Loko just
north of Freetown, the country's capital, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were repulsed by ECOMOG force after incurring heavy
looses, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Kabbah supported by the
Nigeria-led ECOMOG forces signed a ceasefire accord Tuesday in the
Togolese capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire is to last while envoys from both sides could
start direct negotiations in Lome for a comprehensive peace accord
ending the country's eight-year-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the rebels have been stepping up
their efforts of controlling more lands especially in the diamond
mining area to gain more weight in the U.N.-sponsored negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations had earlier flew President Kabbah and rebel
leaders to Lome to kick start the much-desired peace talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton's special envoy Jesse Jackson also
reportedly flew to Lome with Kabbah to join the talks.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Foday Sankoh and his guerrilla leadership had
earlier held internal talks on their uniformed stands in Lome over
the past three weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
