<HEADLINE> GM Food Safe to Eat, Says UK Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The British government spelled out
its position on genetically-modified (GM) food Friday, saying that
GM food on sale in the UK is safe to eat and its development would
be closely watched.
</P>
<P>
There was "no current evidence to suggest that the GM
technologies used to produce food are inherently harmful",
Britain's Cabinet Office Minister Jack Cunningham told the House
of Commons.
</P>
<P>
GM technology could lead to more nutritious and tasty food and
many other benefits, he said, admitting that the risks had to be
"rigorously assessed".
</P>
<P>
In a move to end the continuing row about the safety of GM
products, Cunningham declared that the British government is
setting up two new advisory bodies to examine developments in this
field.
</P>
<P>
The Human Genetics Commission will assess the impact of GM
products on healthcare and another body, called Agricultural and
Environment Biotechnology Commission, will look at the effects of
GM products on agriculture and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Announcing tough voluntary rules on planting GM crops,
Cunningham said that there may have to be legislation on the
subject in the future.
</P>
<P>
"Unrestricted commercial cultivation of GM crops will not
proceed until we are satisfied that they cause no harm to the
environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham also announced the publication of several reports
including one from the government's top medical and scientific
advisors, which recommended a national surveillance unit to
monitor any risk to health from GM food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
