<HEADLINE> Russia Says Humanitarian Scheme Not Enough to Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to the
United Nations, Sergey Lavrov, said on Friday that the
humanitarian scheme alone could not solve the humanitarian crisis
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Lavrov made the statement to the press before the United
Nations Security Council is going to vote on the extension of U.N.
oil-for-food program in Iraq this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Lavrov said the adoption of a U.N. resolution on the extension
of the program was a step which maybe unavoidable in order not
to interrupt the humanitarian scheme in Iraq, but it was not
enough to solve the humanitarian crisis facing the country, Lovrov
said.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian crisis could not be solved by the
humanitarian scheme alone and there must be efforts to revitalize
the social and economic infrastructure in Iraq, Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador reiterated once again the urgent need of arrival
of a radical settlement of the current deadlock involving
introducing of a new monitoring and disarmament mechanism in
conjunction with relieving the burden of the economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Unless these efforts were made, the humanitarian crisis in Iraq
could not be alleviated, Lavrov added.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to decide the continuation of
the U.N. oil-for-food program in Iraq for another six months
under which Iraq is allowed to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth
of oil to buy necessities for its people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq complained to the United Nations early this week that the
only way to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people is lifting all
the sanctions unconditionally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
