<HEADLINE> Chiluba Denies Assisting Angolan Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba has said
it would be stupid for Zambia to frustrate efforts to end the
civil war in Angola after having worked for years seeking a
peaceful solution to the conflict in that country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said this at the State House Friday while meeting with
the Canadian Permanent Representative at the United Nations and
Chairman of U.N. 's Sanctions Committee on National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) Robert Fowler.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia had never engaged in assisting anybody to
destabilize Angola because it had no resources to throw away
carelessly.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted that this was the second time the U.N. was
sending a team to verify charges levelled against Zambia by
Angola.
</P>
<P>
The first mission proved that there was no truth in the
allegation that Zambia was assisting UNITA rebels "because we find
it strange and we do not know what triggered the accusations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He further said certain places which are mentioned by the
Angola do not exist or have the capacity for the work they are
supposed to be capable of.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia did not have the capacity and the desire to
destabilize Angola which had for two decades been robbed of
development due to civil war.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba further said Zambia has complied with the U.N. in all
areas that it was instructed to do and had acted in good faith.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fowler said his committee admires Chiluba's efforts
in trying to bring peace to the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
He said the current position in the region where there were
civil wars was dangerous and can lead to the destabilization of
the region.
</P>
<P>
Fowler said his team did not come to judge but bring message to
the Zambian government and find out the sanction bursting by the
UNITA and put an end to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
