<HEADLINE> New U.N. Special Envoy Named for Western Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has designated William Eagleton, a U.S. diplomat, as his
Special Representative for Western Sahara, and has informed the
U.N. Security Council accordingly, a U.N. statement said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council took note of the Secretary-General's
decision today," said the statement, issued by the U.N. spokesman
here.
</P>
<P>
The new Special Representative of the Secretary-General is
expected to assume his functions at the headquarters of the United
Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) in
Laayoune by early June.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General has also decided to appoint the former
Chairman of the Identification Commission of MINURSO, Robin
Kinloch, as the Deputy Special Representative for Western Sahara,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Eagleton served with the United Nations as Special Coordinator
for the Restoration of Essential Services in Sarajevo from 1994 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
His latest appointment in the national service was that of the
U.S. ambassador to Syria from 1984 to 1988. Eagleton, father of
eight, speaks Arabic, French and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
His predecessor, Charles Dumbar of the United States, has
finished his two-year terms of office on March 31, and he did not
expect to go beyond the end of his tenure simply "for personal
reasons," U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
Accepting Dumbar's resignation, Annan in his March 22 report to
the Security Council voiced his thanks to the outgoing special
envoy for "his great efforts in promoting the peace process in
Western Sahara."
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N. peace plan, the transition period is expected
to start in Western Sahara in June or July, and the referendum
will take place in December to decide the future of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
