<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandans Angered by U.N.Court Verdict on Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The 25-year jail term sentence for
Rwandan genocide criminal Obed Ruzindana Friday provoked angry
reactions among the survivors in general and those residing in
western Kibuye where he killed thousands of Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
"These people deserved capital punishment, but as you know the
International Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) does not accept such
sentence," the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) quoted Rwandan General
Prosecutor Simeon Rwagasore as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ruzindana was punished like someone who was involved in a
simple robbery case, said the general prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
Either his age or his lack of education are not enough reason
to give him such a lighter sentence, another Rwandan official
said.
</P>
<P>
Ruzindana and the former prefect of Kibuye, Clement Kayishema,
were both charged by the ICTR with perpetrating the genocide and
crimes against humanity, inciting to commit genocide in their home
region of Kibuye.
</P>
<P>
They were responsible for the killings of several thousands of
Tutsis at the local church, soccer stadium, and the Bisesero Hills
from April to July in 1994.
</P>
<P>
While Kayishema was sentenced to life imprisonment, the ICTR
gave a 25- year imprisonment to the surprise of many Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
The judges had claimed that his young age, 32 at the time of
genocide, would give him a chance to be reintegrated in the
society.
</P>
<P>
But Rwandan officials said that Ruzindana did not deserve any
clemency as long as he never acknowledged the crimes he had
committed.
</P>
<P>
"We do not understand how the ICTR could hand down different
sentences to both men who teamed up in all the massacres of Tutsis
... They were seen always together at the helm of the killers,''
one woman who lost her husband and all her children declared on
the state-run Radio Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Like this woman, the genocide survivors of Kibuye felt betrayed
by the ICTR which they blamed for not taking into account the
crimes both criminals had committed in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Judicial officials in Kibuye were embarrassed by the
pronouncement of such lenient punishment for a genocide criminal.
</P>
<P>
The trial of Kayishema-Ruzindana lasted for two years and over
80 witnesses were heard by the ICTR.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the U.N. tribunal had handed down sentences to four
Rwandan genocide criminals. Notably, the former Mayor of Taba,
Jean Paul Akayezu, and former interim prime minister, Jean
Kambanda, were sentenced to life imprisonment. Omar Serushago who
was the head of the militia in Gisenyi got 15 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Says Oil-For-Food Plan Short to Meet Aims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. oil-for-food
program in Iraq could not meet all the humanitarian needs of the
Iraqi people, nor could it restore Iraq's economic and social
infrastructure to pre-1990 levels, a senior U.N. official on
Friday quoted U.N. chief Kofi Annan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the United Nations Security Council on the
humanitarian situation in Iraq this morning, Benon Sevan,
Executive Director of Office of the Iraq Program, said the
program was seriously short of the revenue required to meet its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Sevan said over phase IV and V of the program, the oil
revenues had not come close to the ceiling of 5.2 billion U.S.
dollars authorized.
</P>
<P>
In phase V, which expires on May 24, 1999, the final revenue
figure would be 3.8 billion U.S. dollars, still 1.4 billion below
the ceiling, Sevan said.
</P>
<P>
For phase IV and V combined, the deficit in terms of spending
on the humanitarian program was more than 2.5 billion dollars,
and well over 3 billion if taking into account of the need to fund
oil industry spare parts and equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the recent upward trend in the price of oil has
not solved the difficulties encountered in meeting the objectives
of the program, Sevan added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
