<HEADLINE> Silver Resilient Through a Turbulent 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON May 21 (Xinhua) - In the face of difficult economic
conditions in 1998, silver showed resilience through the turbulent
year, posting its best price performance in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
Silver's strong performance in market was the result of steady
industrial fabrication demand and strong investment interest,
according to World Silver Survey 1999 released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, for the tenth consecutive year, the market continued
to have a structural deficit, causing the continued erosion of
above-ground stocks of silver in bullion and coin from by nearly
105 million ounces, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
After three years of growth, fabrication demand fell by 2.2
percent in 1998 to 840.6 million ounces. The fall in the world
total was primarily the result of a sharp decline in East Asia and
Indian fabrication demand.
</P>
<P>
The Silver Institute said in its survey that total supply of
silver to the market declined by 2 percent last year, despite
gains in three main sources of supply: mine production, scrap and
official sector sales.
</P>
<P>
While silver mine production increased for the fourth
consecutive year, up 5 percent, reaching a new record level of
545.5 million ounces, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
