<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Launch Police Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has
decided to set up a police science institute which will open in
August this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here Friday, Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi said the purpose of launching the institute is to
train and provide cadres with higher education for the police
force so as to promote the efficiency of the police and make them
play a better role in the social development.
</P>
<P>
As the first phase, personnel from the interior ministry and
its affiliates will be enrolled, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Then, just as the Higher Institute of the International
Relations, the police institute will be opened to non-police
personnel, he noted. The Institute of the International Relations
used to be operated to train diplomats and now it is also open to
people of other ministries.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that the fund for establishing the police
institute would mainly come from the government's budget, but
foreign donations would be most welcome.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi pointed out that with the opening of the new institute,
other police training centers will still be in operation.
</P>
<P>
Most of the teachers the new institute needs will be
Mozambicans while some foreign experts will also be employed for
some special courses which the natives are not qualified, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the corruption among the judicial departments, the
prime minister said that Mozambique has a new organizational
regulation which will award or punish the police staff according
to how they have carried out their duties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mocumbi noted that those police officers with little
 schooling will be asked to retire and a certain diploma will be
required for new comers.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are five higher educational institutions
including one comprehensive university, one teachers' college and
one institute of foreign affairs, with some 10,000 students on the
campus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
