<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Obasanjo Facing Tough Challenges Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A few days to the handing over of
power from military to civilian, President-elect General Olusegun
Obasanjo is scheduled to be sworn in as the president of the
Fourth Republic of Nigeria on May 29.
</P>
<P>
If all goes well, Nigeria will be a democracy by noon of that
day, bringing an end to the 16 years of uninterrupted military
rule in the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo has pledged to run "an open, fair and transparent
government" throughout his four-year tenure last March after he
won the February 27 presidential election on the ticket of the
People's Democratic Party (PDP).
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that General Obasanjo, who regained power
after he handed over the power to an elected government in 1979,
would face tough challenges to realize his campaign promise of
"revitalizing the Nigerian state and once again put a smile on the
faces of our long suffering people."
</P>
<P>
They noted that to promote the ideals of democracy, national
unity and good governance, the in-coming government of Obasanjo
must tackle the following main challenges:
</P>
<P>
Confidence building: Many Nigerians have lost faith in either
military or civilian governments because of the persisting failure
of previous administrations to deliver the good life to the
people.
</P>
<P>
Governance change: As Nigeria has been under military rule for
about 30 years since its independence in 1960, the due process of
civil society and the rule of law has been undermined, thus
weakening key institutions like the civil service, judiciary and
the police.
</P>
<P>
Poverty Alleviation: More than 65 percent of Nigerians are
living below the poverty line and with the increasing gap between
the few rich and many poor, poverty alleviation can no longer be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
Corruption combat: Corruption is one cankerworm that has eaten
deep into the fabric of the Nigerian society and Nigeria was
recently ranked by Transparency International, a non-governmental
watchdog, as one of the most corrupt countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Debt relief: As at the end of 1998, the stock of public
external debt recorded 28.8 billion U.S. dollars and Nigeria's
ratio of debt/GDP (gross domestic product) is 70 percent. It is
practically impossible for Nigeria to achieve growth unless the
burden is substantially reduced.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure improvement: Energy and electricity supply has
increasingly worsened in recent years, leading to huge negative
impact on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Niger Delta crisis solution: Oil production has left large
parts of the Niger Delta region polluted, making it difficult for
local farmers and fishermen to earn a legitimate living from their
traditional occupations.
</P>
<P>
So, many Nigerians doubt whether the in-coming government will
be able to deliver the promise of democracy as General Obasanjo is
seen as "part of the muddle of the past and a likely pawn in the
hands of the military."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that it is essential for the Obasanjo
government to take deliberate measures to get Nigeria out of the
woods, especially in the first 100 days of his administration.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo needs to swiftly embark on measures to empower
civil institutions to resume their responsibilities and to carry
out reforms of the military and the law enforcement agencies, and
to repeal all legislations which inhibit democracy, they added.
</P>
<P>
However, the president-elect confidently said at his first
press conference after his election victory that he would restore
the dignity of Nigeria, revive the civil institutions and
reinvigorate the battered economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Nigeria had for too long had governments of
"deception and oppression" which have never lived up to their
promises.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo pledged that his first business when he takes
over the reins of government would be to reconcile the Nigerians,
heal their wounds and restore the people's trust in the
government.
</P>
<P>
He promised to lead by example to fight corruption,
professionalize the military and revitalize the economy, and urged
Nigerians to look ahead positively and work hard to turn Nigeria
into the real giant of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, General Obasanjo noted that democracy is a
process, not an event, adding that after so many years of
non-democratic governance, Nigerians have acquired a number of
undemocratic attitude and it would take time to effect the change
of attitude.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the president-elect has asked Nigerians not to expect
miracle from him or think that the country's problems would be
wiped out overnight.
</P>
<P>
On the future of Nigeria, out-going Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar predicted on the occasion of his recent
meeting with National Assembly (parliament) members-elect that the
Fourth Republic of Nigeria would be stable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
