<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Meets Obligations on Nuclear Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has fulfilled all
the major obligations under the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) by signing a facility pact with the provisional
technical secretariat responsible for the treaty, the Foreign
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The facility accord was signed in Vienna Thursday by South
Africa's permanent representative in Vienna, Nozipho Joyce
Mxakato-Diseko, and the secretariat's executive secretary,
Wolfgang Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is only the third country to have concluded such a
deal, and is the first nation in which the agreement is entirely
in effect, the Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The pact grants the secretariat legal authority to undertake
work on South African territory to build up and operate five
stations that South Africa is hosting as part of the international
monitoring system to verify compliance with test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry deputy director for disarmament, Stephen
McQueen, said that the stations were among 321 envisaged
facilities across the world that would monitor compliance.
</P>
<P>
They would transmit data to an international center in Vienna,
and the information would be available to all signatories to the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
"The conclusion of the agreement confirms South Africa's
continuing commitment to the entry-into-force of the CTBT, and
also demonstrates South Africa's readiness to contribute toward
efforts to enhance international peace and security by promoting
nuclear non-proliferation and disarmament," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Signing of the facility agreement complements South Africa's
ratification of the CTBT on March 30, it said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is one of the 17 nations to have ratified the
CTBT. To come into effect, the treaty needs 44 countries to
ratify it.
</P>
<P>
Under article one of the test ban treaty, each state party
"undertakes not to carry out any nuclear weapon test, explosion or
any other nuclear explosion, and to prohibit and prevent any such
nuclear explosion at any place under its jurisdiction or control".
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
