<HEADLINE> Greece: More European Countries Oppose NATO Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Many countries in Europe opposed the
use by NATO of ground forces in Yugoslavia and desired an
immediate end to the Yugoslav crisis through negotiations on the
basis of the draft agreement recently by seven Western countries
and Russia, known as the Group of Eight, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said at a press briefing that the time was right for
both Belgrade and the international community to intensify efforts
for a political solution to the crisis through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Greek government's view was that there
were some grounds for optimism for a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis discussed the
latest developments in the Yugoslav problem in telephone
conversations with German Chancellor Gerhard Shroeder and Italian
Premier Massimo D'Alema, the spokesman said, adding that Simitis
was also in daily contact with other European leaders.
</P>
<P>
Simitis also chaired Friday a meeting to discuss the difference
in the position adopted by the U.S. on the one hand and most
European countries on the other.
</P>
<P>
As for Greece's refusal to allow the use of Greek airspace by
Turkish military aircraft flying to Germany to join NATO air
forces participating in the Yugoslav conflict, he said that it was
the first time such a request had been made and underlined
Greece's categorical opposition to Greek airspace being used for
these types of operations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey reportedly submitted the request to the Greek Foreign
Ministry Thursday, seeking permission for two or three aircraft to
pass through Greek airspace, but Greece rejected the request on
the grounds that Athens was neither taking part in NATO military
operations nor providing facilities to those countries which were
participating in the operations.
</P>
<P>
Greece said Friday that it had already made the necessary
preparations for sending a 500-member peacekeeping force in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greece also reiterated that it would not be
providing Kosovo Albanian refugees with shelter on its territory
but was willing to help them go to other countries. 
</P>
