<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Develop New Bone Marrow Transplant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have proved that it
is possible to transplant bone marrow from mismatched human donors
without the usual pre-transplant destruction to the recipients.
</P>
<P>
At present, some terminally-ill cancer sufferers are not able
to undergo bone marrow treatment because doctors think they are
too ill, weak or old to survive the pre-transplant chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
Bone marrow transplantation recipients usually undergo a
process called ablation, in which their diseased bone marrow is
destroyed by chemotherapy to wipe out their immune system, so that
it does not reject the new marrow.
</P>
<P>
But researchers from the Massachusetts General Hospital, the
United States, reported Friday in The Lancet medical journal they
have successfully treated two terminally-ill patients with a
process that removes the need for such high doses of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The new technique involves blending together the immune systems
of donor and host which both removes the need for the
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The researchers studied five patients who were terminally-ill
with Hodgkins Lymphoma, a cancer of the body's lymphatic system,
using this pioneering technique.
</P>
<P>
Among the five patients, two died from the disease and one for
another reason.
</P>
<P>
But the other two are now in "long-term remission", meaning
they are currently free of disease, which showed the possibility
of a lasting combination of donor and recipient immune systems
without the usual toxic treatment.
</P>
<P>
The technique not only means that more patients without
identically-matched bone marrow donors can receive treatment, it
may also be of use in preventing rejection of transplanted organs,
the researchers believed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0045 </DOCNO>
