<HEADLINE> Khatami's Visit Boosts Tehran-Riyadh Ties: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The recent trip to Saudi Arabia by
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami was a turning point in
Tehran-Riyadh relations and would serve to boost bilateral
economic ties, said an Iranian minister on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Building mutual confidence and understanding was the most
significant achievement of President Khatami's visit to Saudi
Arabia, Commerce Minister Mohammad Shariatmadar told the Islamic
Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Iran and Saudi Arabia amounted to over
100 million U.S. dollars in the past few months, and by taking
into account the indirect trade between the two countries, the
figure is expected to stand at about 400 million dollars, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami Thursday concluded an eight-day
ground-breaking tour to Syria, Saudi Arabia and Qatar, in which
he spent five days on talks with Saudi leaders.
</P>
<P>
Both Iran and Saudi Arabia expressed their national will to
expand economic cooperation and called for strengthening of
joint-economic commission and removal of trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
The second session of the Tehran-Riyadh joint economic
commission is to be held before the year end in Tehran, he said,
adding that Iran can meet the needs of Saudi Arabia for vehicles,
auto parts, clothing, foodstuffs and petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed an agreement on air
transportation based on which Saudi flights to Tehran and
Mashhad and the flights from Iran to Riyadh and Dhahran are
to start by June 20 this year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Simultaneous with Khatami's visit to Saudi Arabia,
representatives of two Saudi petrochemical companies - Saudi Basic
Industries Corp (SABIC) and Saudi Arabian Fertilizer Co. (SAFCO)
have started operation in Iran, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement on the issuance of
commercial visa to Iranian traders and inked a draft of a
protocol on customs, sea transportation, transit, tourism,
physical training, standard as well as protection of bilateral
investment, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to jointly construct factories
producing construction material, fire bricks and high voltage
cables, as well as industrial slaughter houses and cooperate in
fish culture.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia agreed to build a power plant on Qeshm island in
the Persian Gulf, to invest in an international airport and to
make contributions to oil, gas and petrochemical industries in
Iran, the minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
