<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Immediate Approval of Juvenile  Crime Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday urged the House of Representatives to "immediately"
approve the juvenile crime bill passed in the Senate Thursday and
reject the Republican plan to let the explosive debate cool off
until next month.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the House to take immediate action," Clinton
said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
He pressed the House to approve "every one" of the Senate
bill's new restrictions on gun control, which were propelled to
passage Thursday in the wake of high school shootings in Colorado
and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
"We can't once again let the gears of politics as usual grind
our urgency into dust," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Clinton is urging House Democrats to
insist on passing gun restrictions beyond those approved by the
Senate, administration and Democratic aides said.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't settle" for the Senate's limited restrictions,
such as mandatory background checks for all firearms transactions
at gun shows and pawn shops, Clinton told 18 House Democrats
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the group the House should pass additional
provisions that would raise from 18 to 21 the legal age for
possessing and purchasing handguns, semiautomatic assault weapons
and high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
The aides said Clinton delivered that message to the House
Democrats during a private White House meeting to plot strategy in
the gun control debate.
</P>
<P>
Democrats were united in pushing for House action on those
issues by the Memorial Day at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
However, majority Republicans refused to budge from their plans
for Judiciary Committee hearings on the matter Thursday and floor
debate in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
House Republicans were eager to let the issue cool off after it
caused a public relations meltdown for their party during two
volatile weeks of Senate debate on gun control.
</P>
<P>
The shootings in a Colorado and Georgia have generated public
pressure on the Congress to tighten the legislation of gun
control. As many as 15 people were killed in Colorado in a
school shooting on April 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
