<HEADLINE> Camilla Martin Advances into Women's Singles Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Camilla Martin became the first
European shuttler to move into the women's singles final of the
World Championships since 1977 when she defeated Gong Ruina of
China 6-11, 11-9 and 11-3 Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Dannish player looked brilliant in the match in which she
lost the first set but found back her form in the next two sets,
winning the match in a dominating style.
</P>
<P>
Second seeded Gong Ruina, one of the top favorites to win the
world championship, jumped to lead 8-4 in the second set, but lack
of strength and stamina caused her first world title.
</P>
<P>
"She did not have much strength in the second half of the
second set," said Martin, who moved into the top four by defeating
China's Gong Zhichao Friday night. "I was a little bit lucky to
win," she added.
</P>
<P>
Martin will meet Dai Yun of China or Mette Sorensen of Denmark
in the
final.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy to be in the final, and I don't care who I will
play next match," she said.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles of the Sudirman Cup final last Saturday,
Martin lost to Dai Yun in a three-set gruelling match.
</P>
<P>
Chinese team women's singles coach Tang Xuehua said Gong's
defeat was caused by her strength. "She played quite well in the
first set, but in the next two sets, she was obviously lack of
power, and therefore she could only play rallies from the back
court," he said.
</P>
<P>
"When she was at 8-4 lead in the second set, she had chance to
win," Tang continued. 
</P>
