<HEADLINE> Anwar Files Appeal Against Conviction, Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Anwar Ibrahim Saturday filed a
petition of appeal against his conviction and six years' jail
sentence imposed by the High Court when he was found guilty of
interfering in police investigations into allegations of sexual
misconduct against him last month.
</P>
<P>
The petition, which contained 29 grounds, was filed at the
Court of Appeal Registrar's Office by S.N. Nair, one of his 10
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah, and their son were also present.
</P>
<P>
On April 14, Justice Augustine Paul sentenced Anwar to six
years' jail on each of four charges of corrupt practice and
ordered the sentences to run concurrently commencing on that day.
</P>
<P>
In his grounds of appeal, Anwar claimed that the sentence
imposed on him by the High Court was manisfestly excessive.
</P>
<P>
He said the judge failed to exercise his discretion judicially
in that he allowed himself to be influenced by irrelevant
questions and failed to take into account or to give due regard to
questions relevant to the imposition of sentence.
</P>
<P>
"The refusal by the judge to take into account the period
during which I was in prison on remand was unreasonable," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that due to the undue length of the record of
appeal and the numerous legal issues involved, he would apply for
leave to apply for a further and supplementary petition of appeal.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
