<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Free from Rinderpest: Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Ministry of
Agriculture declared here Saturday that the Horn of Africa state
is temporarily free from rinderpest, a major cattle-killer
contagious disease.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said a relevant establishment organized under the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) with the financial assistance
of the European Union had conducted a 10-year inoculation campaign
against rinderpest in 34 African countries including Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveillance conducted jointly by the OAU and pertinent
institutions of the countries where the inoculation campaign had
been carried out proved that most of the target states including
Ethiopia have arrested the disease.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopia proclaimed itself a rinderpest free zone on May 1 in
line with the International Animal Health Organization criteria,"
the ministry was quoted by the official Ethiopian News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said efforts are underway to preempt the spread
into the country of rinderpest prevailing along the southern Sudan
and western Somali frontiers.
</P>
<P>
It said Ethiopia would intensify its rinderpest control
activities to prevent the disease from resurfacing.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has the largest livestock population in Africa. The
Ethiopian government asked the Food and Agricultural Organization
of the United Nations (FAO) in January this year to issue
directives to those countries that boycotted cattle trade with it,
assuring them that the cattle disease is non-existence in
Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
