<HEADLINE> Mozambican Ruling Party Preparing for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Mozambican Liberation
Front (Frelimo) is preparing for the presidential and
parliamentary elections scheduled for October this year, Manuel
Tome, Secretary General of the party said.
</P>
<P>
One of the important measures taken by the party is to hold
three key meetings in June, Tome is quoted by Noticias daily as
saying at a press conference here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three meetings includes the second special meeting of the
central committee of Frelimo on June 4, in which a five-year
government work plan (2000-2004) is expected to be mapped out.
</P>
<P>
The second key meeting of the ruling party, to be attended by
about 500 cadres including all the central committee members, will
discuss ways for the party's campaign in the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
The third meeting will study the implementation of the
government work during the 1995-1999 period, discuss the next
five-year plan and give final touch on the party's campaign
principles, and adopt the election campaign rules for the party.
</P>
<P>
Another content for the meeting is to evaluate and pass the
standards for the presidential and parliamentary candidates in the
elections, Tome said, noting that many citizens and Frelimo party
members wish to see President Joaquim Chissano to run for another
term of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Tome also said he believed that Frelimo can win the second
multi-party elections, because the party has done a "good job" in
the last five years, and it has been preparing for the elections
since 1995, with two million party members in 23,000 party
branches throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The first multi-party elections in Mozambique was held in
October, 1994, in which the Frelimo party won 129 of the 250 seats
in parliament, and Chissano won as the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
