<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jesse Jackson Calls for World Attention to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
special envoy Jesse Jackson has said there is hope for Africa if
the people of the continent themselves realized their worth.
</P>
<P>
But what is more important is for the world to turn its
attention to Africa as it is doing for Europe, Asia, and others,
he said Friday, citing the situation in Kosovo and the carnage in
Sierra Leone war, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"We must open the keyhole and see the door - there is big
Africa full of work and possibility. The world must hear that
story," Jackson, special envoy for democratization and human
rights, told the closing plenary of the Fifth African-African
American Summit, presided over by Ghanaian President Jerry John
Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
At least a dozen African heads of state, vice-presidents and
the King of Swaziland participated in the summit, along with more
than 4, 000 delegates, mostly African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
The event is co-sponsored by the government of Ghana, a host
of American companies including Chevron, and some Ghanaian
companies: the Volta River Authority, and Ashanti Gold fields.
</P>
<P>
 It was organized by the Rev Leon Sullivan, founder of the
U.S-based Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OIPC) who is
also the convener, and the Ghana Investment Promotion Center on
the theme: "Business, Trade and Investment - - Africa can
compete."
</P>
<P>
Jackson said Africans and African Americans must find a common
ground to move on to higher ground. "That is our burden. That is
our challenge. That is our responsibility."
</P>
<P>
 He focused on what he termed the "psychological shift" that
has impacted on Africa and prompted it to embrace democracy,
economic growth, development and progress.
</P>
<P>
"The most profound shift that must take place at the
crossroads is to look to the future," he said, but added that
there was no future in promoting war and discord.
</P>
<P>
Jackson, who mediated a cease-fire agreement in Sierra Leone
earlier this week in Lome, Togo, told the gathering that there
will now be peace in that country along with Eritrea, the
Democratic Republic of Congo and Sudan, "because war is
unacceptable, because peace is the only option." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
