<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian MP says Kosovo Best Served by Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The scenes of desolation and
devastation in Kosovo are so horrible that NATO needs to suspend
its bombing campaign to try to kick-start peace negotiations,
Canadian parliamentarian Svend Robinson said after a quick tour of
the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
The Canada's New Democratic Party MP, who initially supported
the air war when it began on March 24, now believes that the cause
of the displaced Kosovo Albanians is best served by a pause in the
attacks, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"What does NATO have to lose? The important thing is to get to
the negotiating table," Robinson said in a telephone interview
Friday. He was the first Canadian parliamentarian allowed into
Kosovo on Wednesday by the Yugoslav government since the start of
the war.
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslav officials accompanied him during his 24-hour-
visit in Kosovo. They wanted him to view damage caused by bombs of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization in Pristina, the provincial
capital, and elsewhere in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said he saw scores of burned-out or abandoned houses in more
than a dozen villages along the road. "It was just like ghost
towns."
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians may still be hiding
in the mountains and forests of Kosovo and be in danger of
starvation, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
The need to get food, medicine and humanitarian assistance to
these innocent civilians is another reason for NATO to suspend
bombing operations, the MP said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a humanitarian crisis there and as long as NATO is
bombing nobody can get in there," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
