<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Spend $1,651M in 1999/2000 Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
planned to spend a total of 1,164 billion Tanzanian shillings, or
1,651 million U.S. dollars (one to 705) in the 1999/2000 fiscal
year, according to an official report issued by local media
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report was made by Minister for Finance Daniel Yona Friday
when he briefed members of two parliamentary committees for
economy, finance and social services in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Yona said among the total expenditure, which is a 15.5 increase
over last year's 1,008 billion shillings, 921.1 billion shillings
will be for recurrent expenditure and 242.9 billion shillings for
development expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure is expected to be realized by 822.5
billion shillings from internal sources and 388.4 billion
shillings from external loans and grants.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's fiscal year begins on July 1 and ends on June 30.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the recurrent expenditure, 240.4 billion
shillings will be for salaries of civil servants, 680.8 billion
shillings for other uses which include 201 billion shillings for
social services, 148.2 billion for administration, 140.0 billion
shillings for defense and security.
</P>
<P>
Priority in the next development budget will be given to
health, education, water sectors, road construction and
rehabilitation as well as agricultural activities, said Yona.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said the government would continue to ensure
strict control of expenditure in line with revenue collected
without borrowing from banks in order to further reduce inflation
from 8.8 percent this March to five percent by next June and
increase foreign exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
Commenting the value added tax (VAT) introduced last July, Yona
said it is a success as 12,113 VAT payers out of the estimated
15,000 businessmen have been registered.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same session, Nassoro Malocho, the Minister of
State in the President's Office and vice chairman of the Planning
Commission, also made his presentation.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will sustain the divestiture program in
the next financial year by privatizing at least 50 parastatals.
</P>
<P>
He explained that until last December some 270 parastatals out
of a total of 395 parastatals and companies had been privatized,
adding that the exercise so far was 69.3 percent of the target.
</P>
</TEXT>
