<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Education of Children in Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Although the nine years of
compulsory education has become popular in areas involving nearly
three quarters of Chinese people, resulting in a zero illiteracy
rate among the adults, there still remain many difficulties in the
education of children in poor areas, according to Lu Fuyuan, vice-
minister of Education.
</P>
<P>
Lu was addressing a national conference on women and children,
which opened on May 21, where he said that up to the end of last
year people in more than 2,200 counties nationwide have received
the compulsory education, making up 73 percent of the whole
population.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problems in these areas involve a shortage of
funds, the increasing number of children of school age and a
growing rate of illiteracy, even though 98.9 percent of children
nationwide have attended primary school and 87.3 percent attending
middle school.
</P>
<P>
"The central and local governments allocated some 10 billion
yuan for developing education in poor areas between 1995 and 2000.
The Ministry of Education has also obtained a 380 million yuan
loan from the World Bank for popularizing the compulsory primary
or secondary education in poor areas," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
The central government also set up an annual foundation to
sponsor 600,000 drop-out students from poor families to take up
their schooling again.
</P>
<P>
Lu stressed that the Chinese government also give priorities to
education in poor ethnic areas in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 24,000 primary and
middle schools holding nearly four million ethnic students. China
has also cooperated with the United Nations Children's Fund (
UNICEF) in promoting primary education in China's ethnic
communities in its west areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
