<HEADLINE> Malawi Tobacco Expected to Earn $160 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco, Malawi's major export
earner, is expected to earn about 160 million U.S. dollars this
season, but the scenario may not have negative repercussions, the
Malawi News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
 Grey Msonthi, general manager for Auction Holdings Limited,
was quoted as saying that the country has already realized 50
million dollars from burley tobacco sales in the month the tobacco
auction floors have been operational.
</P>
<P>
"We start with lower leaves. Soon some leaves will start
shooting and this will affect quality. When a buyer realizes that
crop will not be there, they will rush to buy thus prices will go
up," he said.
</P>
<P>
There was good quality tobacco this year with daily sales
registering 23 percent higher than last year, said Msonthi.
</P>
<P>
"Prices are firm. Quality has been extremely good and
presentation by farmers is excellent. We were worried with this
year's heavy rains that quality would be compromised, but farmers
looked after their crops very well," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said initially auction holdings estimated volume
of between 90 to100 million kilograms of burley but recent
estimates put the harvest at 75 million kilograms compared to 114
million kilos yielded last year.
</P>
<P>
He assured that prices of all the three varieties are higher
than last year's with burley pegged at an average of 1.54 dollars
per kilogram from last year's 1.30 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Prices are better this year... They are well above those paid
in Zimbabwe. Even demand for our tobacco is high," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
