<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theft of Fire arms Increases in S. Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South African police
authorities have attributed the increasing violent crimes in the
country to the alarming increase in the number of firearms stolen
and lost.
</P>
<P>
Saturday Star newspaper quoted Sydney Mufamadi, minister for
safety and security, as reporting that in 1998 alone a total of
29,694 fir arms had been reported stolen or lost to the police
forces and troops.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that in addition to the smuggling of firearms
from abroad, South African gangs and vigilante groups are
targeting armories of police stations and military barracks to get
illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
Thefts from these armories are often well organized and are
usually carried out with the assistance of a person working inside
the armory or someone with knowledge of its security procedures.
</P>
<P>
Besides, another source of illegal firearms in South Africa is
the theft or loss of civilian-owned firearms.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from 1994 to 1997 show that the number of reported
lost or stolen firearms has risen steadily, from 7,285 in 1994 to
16,963 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For now, the South African government has identified firearms
as a priority within its National Crime Prevention Strategy.
</P>
<P>
National Police Commissioner George Fivas announced recently
that reducing the number of illegal firearms was a priority. He
expressed belief that through legislation, enforcement and
preventive measures, the police would be able to go some way in
this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
