<HEADLINE> Stuer-Lauridsen Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Danish shuttler Thomas Stuer-
Lauridsen announced retirement from the sport of badminton here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Stuer-Lauridsen, bronze medalist at the Barcelona Olympics,
told a press conference: "It is a difficult decision for me, but
it is definitely a right one."
</P>
<P>
Ranked seventh in the world, the Dane lost to China's Sun Jun 5-
15, 13-15 in the quarter-finals of the 11th World Championships
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The first thought of retirement came last September when Stuer-
Lauridsen had a left ankle surgery. "At that time, I decided to
continue for a few months to see whether how well I could do in
the sport. I have decided then if I could not reach top five, I
should quit," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Danish player, 28, began his badminton career ten years ago
and he had taken part in five world championships, in which his
best result was a semi-final berth at the 1995 World Championships
in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He pointed that money played no part in his decision to quit. "
If I think financially, I may continue two more years," said Stuer-
Lauridsen.
</P>
<P>
But he did not mention his plan after retirement. "I may play
more golf," said the Danish player, who is also a good golf player.
</P>
</TEXT>
