<HEADLINE> Iraq in Urgent Need of Oil Spare Parts, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi oil industry is in
urgent need of spare parts for increasing production capacity
which has been adversely affected by the 1991 Gulf War and the
continuation of U.N. sanctions, an oil official said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of Planning and Studies Department at the Oil
Ministry Falih Hassan told reporters that if spare parts are
available, Iraq can increase its oil production to the
pre-sanctions level of 3.25 million barrels per day (bpd) from
the current 2.65 bpd.
</P>
<P>
The oil official held the U.N. Sanctions Committee responsible
for the delay of approving the contracts Iraq concluded for the
purchase of spare parts under the fourth and fifth phases of the
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase Iraq's production and export capacity,
the U.N. Security Council agreed last year to allow Iraq to
purchase 300 million U.S. dollars worth of oil equipment and
spare parts from the fourth phase of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the U.S. and British representatives in
the Sanctions Committee of blocking the approval of its contracts
under various flimsy pretexts.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said that the number of spare parts contracts for oil
sector which are on hold under the two phases has amounted to 245
contracts out of a total of 673 contracts Iraq signed so far.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraq has only received 14 million dollars worth
of spare parts so far under the contracts signed in the fourth
phase, and that no contracted spare parts under the fifth phase to
expire on May 25 have reached Iraq yet.
</P>
<P>
The oil official expected that Iraq will accomplish marketing
350-360 million barrels of crude oil in the fifth phase
under the contracts concluded with foreign companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
