<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddha's Birthday Celebrated in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The great assembly also served as a worship ritual for the
Buddha's tooth relic, which arrived in Hong Kong Friday afternoon
on a specially chartered flight from Beijing. The holy tooth relic
has been preserved in China for 1,523 years as a supreme national
treasure.
</P>
<P>
For the seven consecutive days from Saturday, the tooth relic
will be placed at the Hong Kong Coliseum for public worship.
</P>
<P>
Officiating guests at the ceremony included Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
Zhao Puchu, president of the Buddhist Association of China, Jiang
Enzhu, director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch and Ye
Xiaowen, director general of the State Administration for
Religious Affairs of China.
</P>
<P>
Among other participants at the ceremony were officials from
the Central government of China and the HKSAR, overseas venerables
from the Buddhist sectors, foreign consuls in Hong Kong,
representatives of monks from China's mainland, religious heads
and local Buddhism believers.
</P>
<P>
As the ceremony started, all participants stood to pay respects
to the Buddha's statue three times and the song "Buddha, the Most
Precious One" was played.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his opening speech, Kowk Kwong, chairman of the
organizing committee, said that for many years millions of Hong
Kong Buddhist disciples had been earnestly seeking to make the
Buddha's birthday as a public holiday and to worship the Buddha's
tooth relic.
</P>
<P>
For non-Buddhists, this provides valuable opportunities to
understand the Buddhist beliefs of compassion and equality, Kowk
Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
Buddhists advocate and promote peaceful coexistence, mutual
respect, harmonious relationships and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We strive to purify our thoughts, overcome our sins and attain
virtue; to rid ourselves of hatred and resolve conflicts so that
our society, our country and the whole world may enjoy peace and
harmony," he said.
</P>
<P>
Buddhism in Hong Kong started to take root during the Song
Dynasty (960-1279). Since then, it has attracted many followers
among the local communities.
</P>
<P>
The 8th day of April on the Chinese Lunar calendar, which falls
on May 22 this year, is believed to be the Buddha's birthday and
this is the 2,543 birthday of the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, there are only two holy teeth
left by Sakyamuni Buddha in the world when the he was cremated
more than 2,500 years ago. One is now kept in Sri Lanka and the
other was brought from India to China about 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Since then, it had been worshipped by successive emperors and
has been classified as a supreme national treasure.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
funds were allocated in 1958 to build a new pagoda beside the
original site in Ling Guang Monastery in Xishan, Beijing on the
mountain side for paying homage and worship.
</P>
<P>
Owing to its sacred status as a national treasure, the
opportunities for public display are rare. To celebrate the great
Buddha's birthday this year, the tooth relic was invited to Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
According Kowk Kwong, an estimated 30,000 visitors will be
received to worship the tooth relic every day and night throughout
the seven days.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Puchu said that in 1956 and 1961, at the request of
Buddhists of Burma and Sri Lanka, the tooth relic was taken to
these two countries on two different occasions and was warmly
welcome.
</P>
<P>
Following the speeches by Kowk Kwong and Zhao Puchu, guests of
honor on the stage and all participants followed the traditional
Buddha's Birthday ceremony, to bathe the Buddha's statue to show
respect to Lord Buddha.
</P>
<P>
Commemorative envelopes and seals have been issued in Hong Kong
for the occasion. An exhibition named the "2000 Years of Buddhism
in China" is being held during the worship period. The exhibition
includes pictures and photographs of famous Buddhist sites and
scenes from the Qin (221-206 B.C.) and Han (206 B.C.-A.D. 220)
Dynasties to modern times.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will be of interest to those who are keen on
Buddhist culture and its implications on Chinese history, religion,
philosophy and arts.
</P>
<P>
Another exhibition, the "Buddhist Social Services in Hong Kong,
" introduces the charity work done by the Hong Kong Buddhist
organizations. Buddhists and Taoists make up the vast majority of
Hong Kong's religious population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
