<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summit on African's Future Ends in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Fifth African-African American
Summit aimed at preparing Africa for the new century ended in
Accra, Ghana Friday with a renewed dedication and commitment from
delegates to lift Africa from poverty to becoming a partner in
the global market.
</P>
<P>
 The Summit, which opened Monday, brought together an
unprecedented 19 Presidents and Heads of Government, 25 City
Mayors from the United States over 300 foreign companies and the
largest number of African Americans "to return to Africa after
slavery," under the theme of " Business, Trade and Investment:
Africa Can Compete."
</P>
<P>
 For the first time in the history of the Summit which started
in 1991 with Abidjan, some definite solutions for the "New Africa"
vision were reached, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
 Among them was the launch of the People's Investment Fund for
Africa (PIFA), outdooring of the Global Sullivan Principles,
Signing of an Agreement between Ghana and the State of Georgia in
the U.S. to help boost tourism in Ghana.
</P>
<P>
 Memoranda of understanding were signed between some African
Companies and their foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
 But, the most significant success was the shared commitment
by the American Mayors, the Black Caucaus in the U.S. and the
Official African American representatives in the White House to
push for the passing of the "African Growth and Opportunity Act."
</P>
<P>
 "Even though that may not be all that we want for Africa, it
will be a strong beginning for bringing Africa in the global
market," said Miss Rosa Whitaker, the White House assistant Trade
Representative for Africa.
</P>
<P>
 The Reverend Jesse Jackson, U.S. President's special envoy
for the promotion of democracy and human rights in Africa, said
that Africa "can go forward with hope" when the bill is passed.
</P>
<P>
 The Growth and Opportunity Act, at least, will give Africa
access to the American market and improve trade relations with the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
 Miss Whitaker said Africa needs about 100 billion dollars to
sustain a growth rate of six to seven percent in a year.
</P>
<P>
 "This cannot come in aid and grants but through investments
and opportunity to be active partners in the world trade," Miss
Whitaker said.
</P>
<P>
 Apart from the consensus on the Act, American businesses were
told to adopt a more proactive and positive outlook to the
numerous business opportunities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
 "We need to free ourselves from the 'ugly American syndrome'
of seeing Africa as a continent with no future," The Reverend Leon
Sullivan, the Convener of the Summit said at a press conference to
close the Summit.
</P>
<P>
 Rev. Sullivan said he appreciated President Clinton's visit
to Africa which was "historic and important" and the efforts he is
making to give Africa a focus on the global play-ground. However,
he said, there is more America can do to help Africa.
</P>
<P>
 "The big thing which we expect America to do is debt relief
for Africa, " Rev. Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
 The issue was also played up at one of the Summit's workshops
-- business and trade and investment -- where concerns were
expressed about the huge debt overhung of the Continent.
</P>
<P>
 About a third of Africa's annual income is spent on servicing
debts to rich Western Nations and multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
 Some of the workshops also dealt with health issues,
agriculture and food security, good governance, education and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
 From a distance, the Summit was a big step toward Africa's
reawakening vision for the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
 "This summit, by far is the most successful of all," the
67-year old Rev. Sullivan, who looked exhausted from preaching
the "new Africa" dream, said.
</P>
<P>
 The success was partly measured by the quick response of the
delegates to PIFA which realized 250,000 dollars at six percent
interest per annum.
</P>
<P>
 Rev. Sullivan said PIFA would be used to support small
businesses and also create about 5,000 new businesses in Africa in
the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
