<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hike in U.S. Interest Rates Won't Affect Asia Greatly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Asian economies can survive an
increase in U.S. interest rates, Mary Bush, former United States
Alternate Executive Director of the International Monetary Fund,
said Friday during a meeting in Cebu City of the Philippines,
Philippines News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, the U.S. Federal Reserve decided to hold the
benchmark federal funds rate at 4.75 percent, but it said it would
consider an eventual raise.
</P>
<P>
Asian economies fear that a hike in U.S. interest rates will
cause global money to rush there and deprive emerging economies of
cash.
</P>
<P>
But Bush said the United States had already "taken care of a
large part of the Asian countries' short-term debt" that are
"coming due all at once."
</P>
<P>
She explained, "With this kind of rationalization of the debt
structure, an increase in U.S. interest rates will not have such a
heavy impact" even if the short-term debt is still there.
</P>
<P>
Bush assured that the Federal Reserve takes into account what
is happening in the rest of the world and "what the risks are on
other economies when they raise interest rates or change interest
rate policies."
</P>
<P>
She said what the Federal Reserve might do is implementing "a
couple of small increase (of interest rates) to calm down
inflationary pressures," which will make the Asian countries
remain in "a much better shape."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Philippine Economic Planning Secretary Felipe
Medalla said "anything (increase) beyond 50 basis points is bad,"
because this would depress stock prices and put pressure on
domestic rates.
</P>
<P>
But the country's Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said
domestic interest rates would be unaffected because the government
had already borrowed enough from international sources to fund
this year's budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
