<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Afghanistan Sign Road Construction Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Afghan Taliban
authorities on Saturday signed an agreement to rebuild a
10-kilometer section of the road leading from the eastern Afghan
town of Jalalabad to the capital city of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Maulvi Saaduddin Saeid, the Taliban senior official responsible
for public Works and a senior official of Pakistan's Foreign
Office (FO) signed the document, an FO statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not mention the cost and the time limit for
the project.
</P>
<P>
Under the direction of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, Pakistan is
actively taking part in rehabilitation and development of
Afghanistan, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The 10-km stretch of the road will be rehabilitated to its
original design during the current financial year and more funds
will be allocated in the next financial year, it added.
</P>
<P>
The project will be managed by "Public Works Ministry" of the
Taliban authorities under the technical supervision of National
Highway Authority of Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
