<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Visits Kuwait to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
Saturday left here for Kuwait on a three-day visit aimed at
promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The visit will be Hoss's fourth leg of his Arab world tour since
he took office from his predecessor Rafik Hariri last December.
</P>
<P>
He has visited Saudi Arabia and Egypt in February, and Qatar
and U.A.E. in March this year.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Hoss will meet Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber
al-Sabah, and Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad
al-Sabah, according to the official itinerary.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is also due to hold talks with the Kuwaiti
ministers of foreign affairs, finance and transport.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the official Kuwaiti News Agency on
Friday, Hoss said he would be discussing the prospects of economic
cooperation and further Kuwaiti investment in Lebanon's
reconstruction plans.
</P>
<P>
As the second largest financial bankroller after Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait has granted Lebanon a total of 331 million U.S. dollars in
donations and soft loans since the end of the country's 1975-1990
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Hoss also reaffirmed Lebanon's position regarding the Iraqi
question, saying Baghdad should release all Kuwaitis seized
during its invasion to the country in 1989 and implement all
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
But he decried the U.N. sanctions on Iraq, citing it's not
fair to punish a population for the mistakes of its
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
