<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt to Make Study Before Investing in CHT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- With assistance from the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), the Bangladeshi government will undertake
a detailed study in September-December this year to identify
various projects before going for massive investment in the
southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracks (CHT).
</P>
<P>
The study, which will be the first major step following the end
of the nearly two decades of insurgencies in the region with the
signing of a peace accord in December 1997, is seen by the local
people as a leap forward from the unplanned development
initiatives in the past.
</P>
<P>
The study will cost 30.3 million taka (620,000 U.S. dollars).
The ADB will provide 500,000 dollars for the study and the rest
will come from the government, The Daily Star Business Saturday
quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
A team of 13 experts -- five foreigners and eight locals --
will be appointed to conduct the study, and it will talk to a
cross-section of local people to ascertain their development
needs, they said, adding that after the study, the team will
prepare a report outlining various projects necessary for
socio-economic development in this long-neglected region.
</P>
<P>
The people in the CHT, which consists of three districts --
Rangamati, Bandarban and Khagrachhari, are hoping that this time
the CHT peace agreement will trigger massive development
activities there.
</P>
<P>
On completion of the study, the ADB and some donor countries
and agencies would come forward with financial assistance to
implement the development projects, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
