<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba's Peace Efforts on Congo (K) Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia-Namibia Permanent
Commission has welcomed Zambian President Frederick Chiluba's
tireless efforts to restore peace in Congo (K) under the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) mandate.
</P>
<P>
This is contained in a communique released here at the
just-ended fifth session of the Zambia-Namibia joint permanent
commission on defense and security held in Namibian capital
Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
The two countries expressed support for the early signing of a
cease- fire agreement in Congo (K) and the deployment of a United
Nations and Organization of African Unity (OAU) peace-keeping
force in that country, Times of Zambia newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On the angola situation, the commission regretted the collapse
of the 1994 Lusaka protocol, which had led to renewed fighting
between the Angolan government and the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels.
</P>
<P>
The commission put the blame on UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
It urged all parties to the conflicts on the continent to
commit themselves to African initiatives aimed at resolving
conflicts peacefully.
</P>
<P>
It also commended the recent SADC peace-keeping exercise Blue
Crane which took place in South Africa, describing it as a
positive step toward capacity building for future operations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to work together in dealing with
the secessionist ambitions being pursued by some misguided people
in the two countries, the communique said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
