<HEADLINE> Estrada Sets Priority of Philippines' Charter Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Economic, not political, reforms are
the priority of the Presidential Palace in seeking amendments to
the 1987 Constitution, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio-TV program "JEEP ni Erap", Estrada also
endorsed the constitutional revision by a constituent assembly,
saying it is more economic than holding a constitutional
convention.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that any political amendment to the Constitution
should take effect only after the end of his six-year term of
office in 2004.
</P>
<P>
"I am more interested in economic reforms because these impact
on our daily lives. Political revisions can wait until after my
term ends," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was also giving the Preparatory Commission on
Constitutional Reforms until early 2000 to study and formulate
recommendations on possible amendments to the 1987 Charter.
</P>
<P>
"We will make proper consultations. We want our Constitution
amended, because it has obsolete provisions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the work of the Preparatory Commission on
Constitutional Reforms, he said: "This should give the constituent
assembly proposed reforms or discussions, and save it from more
studies and debate."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the constituent assembly would be
able to finish its work early so that the people could ratify the
proposed reforms in a plebiscite, to be scheduled simultaneously
with the 2001 Congress elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Adopts Floating Exchange Rate System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government decided
Saturday to adopt a floating exchange rate system to replace the
fixed one the country has been using for over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Aguinaldo Jaime, governor of the Angolan National Bank, said
Friday when he announced the decision that the reason for the new
system is that the country's foreign reserve is "on the brink of
exhaustion", and thus Angola cannot afford to keep a fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
In medium or long terms, the measure will bring positive
influence on the country's economy, as the bank can purchase the
much-needed foreign exchange for the government and adjust the
deposit of its own currency, the kwanza, Jaime noted.
</P>
<P>
What's more important, he said, is that through the new system
the central bank will be able to offer loans to the development
programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Fixed rate system has been in use ever since 1975, when the
country won independence from Portugal. But the re-start of the
costly civil war and the low price of oil on world market have
reduced the country's foreign reserve by one third.
</P>
<P>
Angola was thrown into one of the most serious financial crisis
by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The official rate between the U.S. dollar and kwanza was one to
710,000 Friday, but it was one dollar to two million at the black
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Scientists to Identify Source of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The scientists, together with their international colleagues,
are searching for proof for their theory that the Marburg virus is
the first to have been transmitted by animals to human beings.
</P>
<P>
One theory has it that AIDS was transmitted by a monkey to a
human, who then spread it all over the world. Ebola, too, is
suspected of having been passed on in a chain of eight or nine
viral generations.
</P>
<P>
If the transmitters of the Marburg virus prove to be animals
which can live and reproduce while carrying it, this will have
been the first time in documented history that so many victims
were infected by animals rather than by other humans.
</P>
<P>
Marburg is a town in Germany where the deadly virus was first
documented in 1967. Scientists making a vaccine had handled
monkeys in order to cultivate their cells.
</P>
<P>
So far, 29 people have become infected with Marburg fever
virus, and nine died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
