<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Welcomes MILF's Acceptance of Peace Talks Venue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Saturday welcomed the acceptance by the rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) of a government condition to hold their
peace talks in Philippine territory.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on his weekly radio-TV program "JEEP ni Erap", Estrada
reiterated that the peace talks should take place in the
Philippines, because it is an internal problem of the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is good that they have been enlightened on the issue. My
administration will not allow holding the talks abroad. The
problem is here; so we should solve it here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he was open to having the government and the MILF
hold the peace talks in the main southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"I see no problem with that, so long as the talks are held in
Philippine territory," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is one of two rebel groups now negotiating peace with
the government. The other is the National Democratic Front.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the MILF insisted on holding peace talks with the
government in a "neutral country." But the Estrada administration
stood pat on its position that the negotiations take place in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada said he would let Congress decide on a
proposal by Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) Governor
Nur Misuari to postpone the elections scheduled for this September
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Misuari has claimed the ARMM elections should come after a
plebiscite that will determine the coverage of an expanded ARMM.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to Congress to determine the proper action, if it is
really lawful or not," Estrada said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
