<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees More Foreign Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- There were 121,550 overseas
visitor arrivals during April this year, a five-percent increase
over the same month last year, official figures showed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Acting Government Statistician Dianne
Macaskill said overseas visitor arrivals had increased for the
eighth consecutive month, adding that this April saw more visitors
from Asia, but fewer from Australia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Australia, which is New Zealand's most important source country
for international visitors, contributed one in three of all
short-term visitor arrivals in the month. Visitors from Australia
have increased by 86 percent over the last 10 years and in 1998
alone, New Zealand saw more than 500,000 arrivals of Australian
visitors.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, opposing trends in long-term arrivals
and departures are continuing. In the year ending April 1999,
there were 56,740 arrivals, down about one-third on the 1996
figure of 81,210. In contrast, long-term departures rose from
46,180 in the year ending April 1995 to 67,430 in the year ending
April 1999, a rise of 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the year ending April 1999, long-term departures
exceeded long-term arrivals by 10,700. This is a significant
turnaround from net gains of 19,370 and 2,020 in the previous two
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
