<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Ministers Adopt Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market of Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) Council of Ministers has adopted most of
the recommendations drafted by the inter-governmental committee.
</P>
<P>
The proposals include a call to nations to publish a legal
notice on a 90 percent tariff reduction by the end of this year.
So far only Egypt and Madagascar have done so out of 21 COMESA
members, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The council Friday adopted a recommendation on the launch of a
program to ensure a free trade area by the end of October 2000,
which requires the cut of tariffs among member states by 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
COMESA's secretary-general Erastus Mwencha Friday cleared fears
that governments would lose revenue when COMESA becomes a free
trade region.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said that the strategy would immensely benefit the
private sector by less taxes and tariffs levied by the state
governments.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door council meeting, which started on May 20, is
expected to conclude its deliberations before Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pending recommendations for discussion include the
requirement that COMESA secretariat undertakes a study on air
transport charges for landing and ground services in all member
states for the evolvement of a liberalized aviation industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
