<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Obasanjo Facing Tough Challenges Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A few days to the handing over of
power from military to civilian, President-elect General Olusegun
Obasanjo is scheduled to be sworn in as the president of the
Fourth Republic of Nigeria on May 29.
</P>
<P>
If all goes well, Nigeria will be a democracy by noon of that
day, bringing an end to the 16 years of uninterrupted military
rule in the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo has pledged to run "an open, fair and transparent
government" throughout his four-year tenure last March after he
won the February 27 presidential election on the ticket of the
People's Democratic Party (PDP).
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that General Obasanjo, who regained power
after he handed over the power to an elected government in 1979,
would face tough challenges to realize his campaign promise of
"revitalizing the Nigerian state and once again put a smile on the
faces of our long suffering people."
</P>
<P>
They noted that to promote the ideals of democracy, national
unity and good governance, the in-coming government of Obasanjo
must tackle the following main challenges:
</P>
<P>
Confidence building: Many Nigerians have lost faith in either
military or civilian governments because of the persisting failure
of previous administrations to deliver the good life to the
people.
</P>
<P>
Governance change: As Nigeria has been under military rule for
about 30 years since its independence in 1960, the due process of
civil society and the rule of law has been undermined, thus
weakening key institutions like the civil service, judiciary and
the police.
</P>
<P>
Poverty Alleviation: More than 65 percent of Nigerians are
living below the poverty line and with the increasing gap between
the few rich and many poor, poverty alleviation can no longer be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
Corruption combat: Corruption is one cankerworm that has eaten
deep into the fabric of the Nigerian society and Nigeria was
recently ranked by Transparency International, a non-governmental
watchdog, as one of the most corrupt countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Debt relief: As at the end of 1998, the stock of public
external debt recorded 28.8 billion U.S. dollars and Nigeria's
ratio of debt/GDP (gross domestic product) is 70 percent. It is
practically impossible for Nigeria to achieve growth unless the
burden is substantially reduced.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure improvement: Energy and electricity supply has
increasingly worsened in recent years, leading to huge negative
impact on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Niger Delta crisis solution: Oil production has left large
parts of the Niger Delta region polluted, making it difficult for
local farmers and fishermen to earn a legitimate living from their
traditional occupations.
</P>
<P>
So, many Nigerians doubt whether the in-coming government will
be able to deliver the promise of democracy as General Obasanjo is
seen as "part of the muddle of the past and a likely pawn in the
hands of the military."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that it is essential for the Obasanjo
government to take deliberate measures to get Nigeria out of the
woods, especially in the first 100 days of his administration.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo needs to swiftly embark on measures to empower
civil institutions to resume their responsibilities and to carry
out reforms of the military and the law enforcement agencies, and
to repeal all legislations which inhibit democracy, they added.
</P>
<P>
However, the president-elect confidently said at his first
press conference after his election victory that he would restore
the dignity of Nigeria, revive the civil institutions and
reinvigorate the battered economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Nigeria had for too long had governments of
"deception and oppression" which have never lived up to their
promises.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo pledged that his first business when he takes
over the reins of government would be to reconcile the Nigerians,
heal their wounds and restore the people's trust in the
government.
</P>
<P>
He promised to lead by example to fight corruption,
professionalize the military and revitalize the economy, and urged
Nigerians to look ahead positively and work hard to turn Nigeria
into the real giant of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, General Obasanjo noted that democracy is a
process, not an event, adding that after so many years of
non-democratic governance, Nigerians have acquired a number of
undemocratic attitude and it would take time to effect the change
of attitude.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the president-elect has asked Nigerians not to expect
miracle from him or think that the country's problems would be
wiped out overnight.
</P>
<P>
On the future of Nigeria, out-going Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar predicted on the occasion of his recent
meeting with National Assembly (parliament) members-elect that the
Fourth Republic of Nigeria would be stable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Ugandan Currency Plunges Against Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan currency shilling has
experienced an unprecedented depreciation of 18.9 percent against
the U.S. dollar over the past 10 months, making the local foreign
exchange market much more volatile than ever.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the two currencies stood at 1,230
shillings to one dollar last July when the new fiscal year
started. But it plummeted to a record low of 1,520 shillings to
one dollar by the end of April this year, triggering more and
fresh concerns over the stability of the local currency.
</P>
<P>
In response to public pressure, the Bank of Uganda, the
country's central bank , has pumped large sums of hard-earned
foreign exchange into the market to rescue the falling shilling,
but failed to save it from dropping to the rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
The off-season coffee, fish ban by the European Union, delayed
fund from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and insecurity in
the region are widely held responsible for the sharp shilling
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Coffee exports, which account for some 60 percent of Uganda's
foreign exchange earnings, have been on the decline over this
period.
</P>
<P>
In April alone, the coffee exports nose-dived to 173,031 bags
(50 kilograms per bag) from the previous level of 288,033 bags,
representing a decline of 40 percent in volume. The coffee
returns dropped by 43 percent to 13.45 million dollars in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released by the Uganda Coffee
Development Authority, coffee prices in the international market
have been low because of the sharp increase in Brazil's coffee
exports.
</P>
<P>
The fish ban imposed by the Ugandan government and the EU
respectively helped make the scarcity of dollar a sure thing in
the money market.
</P>
<P>
Since fish poisoning was discovered in Lake Victoria in March
this year, the government banned fish sales in the domestic
markets, followed by the EU ban of fish product exports from the
region.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been the largest buyer of Uganda's fish products. In
the wake of the EU fish ban, Uganda loses one million dollars each
week.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the IMF and other donors delayed their funding to
Uganda, saying the country's defense spending is shooting up to "a
dangerously high level."
</P>
<P>
The defense budget of this financial year was 150 million
dollars, some 2.2 percent of the country's gross domestic product,
while the prescribed rate should be 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and other multilateral financial institutions providing
fund to Uganda have urged the Ugandan government to slash the
defense spending and this was set as a precondition to their
further funding to this fund- thirsty country.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has delayed 18 million dollars pledged to the country
so far this year. Other donors made similar demands.
</P>
<P>
Under the mounting pressures from this donors, the Ugandan
leaders have to agree to reduce the defense spending in the next
fiscal year to 121 million dollars and to earmark all the donated
money for the top priority areas like health, education and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Insecurity in the country and the region as a whole is also to
blame for the weakening shilling. The spilling war in the
Democratic Republic of Congo, frenzy rebel attacks on soft targets
and the recent spate of bombings in capital Kampala are the key
causes of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
This increasing insecurity has scared away prospective
investors and sent foreign investors drawing money from banks to
deposit it in a third country.
</P>
<P>
The safety concern acted as the prime killer to the country's
young but booming tourist industry. The Bwindi massacre in early
March this year, in which eight foreign tourists were killed by
Rwandan Hutu extremists, almost brought the business of tourist
agents to a standstill. Lots of foreign tourists have called to
cancel their planned trips to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Faced with the free fall of shilling, the central bank did not
hesitate to come to its rescue. In April, it injected a total of
25.6 million dollars to calm the market and in early May another
eight million dollars were sold out to stabilize the shilling. But
these efforts did not reverse the falling trend of the currency.
</P>
<P>
Senior economists and officials with the central bank said at a
press conference Thursday that with the coming of another coffee
season at the end of this month, coffee exports would recover and
the demand for dollar would naturally be brought down.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that the shilling would gain against the dollar
very soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Diplomat Demands Probe Result of NATO's Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government should
inform China of the result of the investigation into the recent
attack on the Chinese embassy to Yugoslavia at an earlier date, a
Chinese diplomat said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiaoming, minister of the Chinese Embassy to the United
States, said the U.S. government should speed up the probe into
the raid on the Chinese embassy in Belgrade and make the result
public swiftly to meet all demands of the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
On May 7, NATO forces used five missiles to hit the Chinese
embassy to Yugoslavia at different angles, killing three Chinese
correspondents, injuring more than 20 Chinese diplomatic personnel
and destroying the embassy building.
</P>
<P>
The attack has triggered anger and strong condemnation not only
from the Chinese government and people, but also from over 120
other countries in the world, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He said many Americans, the congressmen and congresswomen in
particular, feel that the Chinese government's demands are
reasonable and that the U.S. government should comprehensively
inform the result of the investigation of the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
China, Liu said, attaches importance to the development of the
Sino-U.S. relationship. "NATO's attack on the Chinese Embassy not
only hurt the feelings of the Chinese people, but also damaged
China-U.S. ties," he said.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. is sincere in improving and developing Sino-U.S.
relations, it should thoroughly, comprehensively and fairly probe
into the missile attack so as to win trust from the Chinese
government and people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu also bitterly criticized U.S. media for their biased and
distorted coverage of the attack on the Chinese embassy, saying
that what they are doing is whitewashing the incident and help the
U.S. government shirk responsibility. 
