<HEADLINE> Rebels Surrender to Ugandan Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 120 armed rebels of the
Uganda National Rescue Front II (UNRFII) have surrendered to the
army following a peace initiative by the government, a security
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Oya Nahori, an official in charge of rebel training programs in
the northwestern West Nile region, was quoted by Saturday's New
Vision as saying over the weekend that the former rebels under Ali
Bamuze are currently undergoing a rehabilitation course in Arua
District.
</P>
<P>
The rebels turned up at various army installations and local
council units in the area for the last one month. They came from
Sudan where they had been operating, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among those who surrendered was a major who served in the Obote
II government and a former government army captain identified only
as Yasin, the report added.
</P>
<P>
At the center, the trainees were given basic knowledge on how
to re- integrate in the society and vocational skills to enable
them to earn a decent living. They also had the option of joining
the army.
</P>
<P>
The government, in conjunction with local councils, recently
set up "Aringa Peace Initiative" to facilitate the return of armed
opposition groups operating from the West Nile Region.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said the initiative could also cover other
rebel groups in Kitgum, Gulu and other parts in the north.
</P>
<P>
During his recent tour of the northern region, President Yoweri
Museveni extended amnesty to rebels and their leaders who would
like to surrender to the government. This is another move by the
government to pacify the region subject to frequent rebel attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
