<HEADLINE> Iran-Gulf Rapproachement not to Affect UAE Stand: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The UAE has no reservations about improving ties with Iran by
some of its fellow Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) members, but the
Iranians might misinterpret this move, UAE's Minister of
Information and Culture Sheikh Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan was
quoted on Saturday by the official WAM news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iran and UAE have been been at odds over the sovereignty of the
three islands of Abu Moussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs which are
located near strategic shipping lanes in the Gulf. The islands are
currently under the control of Iran.
</P>
<P>
The misinterpretation might add to Iranians' intransigence
against the UAE's repeated calls for a peaceful settlement of the
issue through dialog or international arbitration, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
"Tehran always claims that the issue was just a
misunderstanding, but we see in reality that the issue is far
from what Tehran was claiming," the official said.
</P>
<P>
A series of high-level visits between Iran and GCC members
Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Bahrain recently have brighten the
prospect of improving relations between Iran and its former foes
in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has been uneasy over the rapproachement with Iran
by the three GCC members while its dispute with Iran remains
unsolved. The GCC also includes Kuwait and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
