<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up 13,500 Community Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will set up 13,500
community clinics in the rural areas within five years starting
from this year, with a view to providing comprehensive health and
family planning services to the rural people.
</P>
<P>
Five hundred such community clinics will be established this
year, with 100 million taka (about 2.1 million U.S. dollars)
already allocated by the government for this purpose, The
Financial Express daily newspaper Saturday quoted a source of the
Health and Family Welfare Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's health and family planning program, one
clinic will cover 6,000 persons and provide the basic health
services. But depending on the geographic location and density of
population, the number may vary but it should not be more than
7,500 and fewer than 4,500 as it was decided by the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Each clinic will be manned by two government health workers,
one female family welfare assistant and another male or female
health assistant, he said, adding that based on the need of the
rural people, these clinics will work as the "one-stop service
centers."
</P>
<P>
A policy of joint venture between the government and the
related community has been evolved to set up the clinics in order
to involve the rural people in the government's health and family
services. The ministry has already formulated a guideline in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
The government will bear the cost of the construction work and
provide equipment, medicines, furniture and salaries of workers,
while the local community will have to give the land for the
clinics and they will also have to carry out the day-to-day and
long-term maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The government will allocate 150,000 taka (about 30,900
dollars) for the construction of each clinic and medical
equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, general medical treatment, family planning,
immunization of children, antenatal care and other medical
services are provided by various agencies under various programs
and after the establishment of these clinics, these services will
be provided from there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
