<HEADLINE> Cambodia Demands Investigation of US Weapon Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Foreign Ministry
sent a letter Friday to the U.S. Embassy in Cambodia protesting
against its rejection of a check on a shipment of weapon parts
said to have been mistakenly sent to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The spare parts for U.S.-made M-16 assault rifles was found in
a box Monday when the embassy and the Cambodian Mine Action Center
(CMAC) checked a shipment of medical equipment donated by the
United States to the CMAC, the local newspaper Rasmei Kampuchea
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"After this surprised discovery, the embassy staff collected
all the arms parts and transported them to the embassy without
allowing the Cambodian competent authorities to inspect these
weapons," the Foreign Ministry's letter said.
</P>
<P>
It was said that there were at least 10 similar boxes on the
spot, but the boxes were immediately taken into the U.S. Embassy
by embassy staff without opening.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry considers this action of the embassy's staff as a
grave disrespect to the Cambodian laws and regulations relating to
arms control and would like to urge the embassy to return
immediately those arms parts to the Ministry of Interior, so that
the Cambodian authorities can investigate thoroughly this
incident," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy explained later that the rifle parts were
meant to go to Thailand, but were mistakenly sent to Cambodia. And
it was said an apology was already made by the embassy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
