<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0430 GMT, May 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea registered a trade surplus of 464 million
U.S. dollars with the United States in March this year, a three-
month streak of surplus, the Korea Trade-Investment Promotion
Agency said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, which suffered a trade deficit of 271 million
dollars with the United States last December, swung back to a
surplus of 530 million dollars in January this year and 620
million in February. (SKorea-US-Trade Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The European Union has given the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) a grant of 2.5 million U.S.
dollars for strengthening certification of standards of goods
produced in the region.
</P>
<P>
A three-year program is already in place and will facilitate
efforts to expand the capacity of COMESA members' products
standard bureaux, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
John Opio, senior program officer in COMESA's industry division,
said Thursday that the region risked being sidelined in
international trade if its products failed to meet standards set
by external markets. (COMESA-Goods Quality)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Stocks on Brazil's Sao Paulo exchange, the
largest in Latin America, closed down sharply Friday with the
benchmark Bovesa index reducing by 2.98 percent to 11,727 points,
against 12,088 points on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was some 384 million U.S. dollars against 433
million dollars on the previous day. (Brazil-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government reported a surplus of 113.5
billion U.S. dollars last month, 8.9 percent lower than the 124.6-
billion-dollar one posted in April 1998, the Treasury Department
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
April is the month that people face the deadline to pay their
income taxes. In 1997 and 1998, record surpluses for April
provided lawmakers with an unexpected windfall.
</P>
<P>
The April surplus helped congressional and White House
negotiators reach agreement in 1997 on a five-year plan to balance
the federal budget. (US-Federal Surplus) 
</P>
</TEXT>
