<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Parties in Indonesia Join Hands for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Three major political parties in
Indonesia -- the National Mandate Party (PAN), the United
Development Party (PPP) and the Justice Party (KP)-- joined hands
Friday as the general election nears.
</P>
<P>
A seven-point communique issued by the leaders of the three
parties pledged to join reform forces to block the so-called
pro-status quo groups led by the ruling Golkar Party, local
leading newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the joint communique, the parties said they will strive for
democratic, honest, fair and secure elections. They also pledged
to get rid of all anti-reform forces which they say are still
active.
</P>
<P>
"We need to straighten the reform programs because at present
there is a strong tendency toward deviation from the reform
movement," PK's spokesman Ismail said after a closed-door meeting
of the three parties.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said pro-status quo groups are "those maintaining
tyrannical regimes using arms and money and based on feudal
concepts of power and mass support.
</P>
<P>
PAN's chairman Amien Rais said the union aims to attract more
parties in the fight against the pro-status quo groups led by
Golkar.
</P>
<P>
Rais and other reform-minded politicians have launched an open
war against Golkar, once the political vehicle of former President
Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
PAN recently formed a coalition with the popular Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle and the National Awakening Party. The
coalition is widely seen as a massive front with strong grassroots
support and able to topple the Golkar.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar, which had won six general elections when Soeharto
was in power, has split since Soeharto stepped down in May last
year. The party has nominated incumbent President B.J. Habibie as
presidential candidate for the election.
</P>
<P>
A total of 48 parties will contest the forthcoming election,
the first multi-party election in 30 years. The election will
elect 462 members to the 500-seat House of Representatives (DPR).
The remaining 38 seats will be reserved for the Armed Forces which
does not vote.
</P>
<P>
The newly elected DPR will form the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) together with 200 members nominated by the
president. The MPR, the highest legislative body, is expected to
hold a meeting to elect the next president and vice president in
November this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
