<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ends Meeting on Science, Technology in Yangon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) Committee of Science and Technology ended its 37th
meeting here Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, which began Wednesday, discussed
successful completion of seven projects in various areas of
regional cooperation in science and technology. They include
telecommunications training, multimedia archive development,
energy co-generation from biomass resources, natural gas
utilization in transport, coastal zone environment and research
management and remote sensing and geographic information systems.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed to prepare a strategic plan for implementing
its programs and other science- and technology-based activities
that are included in the Hanoi Plan of Action adopted by the Sixth
ASEAN Summit held in Hanoi in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the need to assist new ASEAN member countries
to be more rapidly integrated into the mainstream of science and
technology cooperation in the region. The committee will put
together human resources development packages designed to
strengthen science and technology institutions in the new member
countries.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, training in food science and technology will
be offered by Thailand to Myanmar as a start.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Myanmar to host a meeting of the
committee after the country joined the ASEAN in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The committee is to hold its 38th meeting in Singapore in
October 1999.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
