<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Banks' Rates Policy Arouses Criticism (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Thailand was plunged into recession two years ago, the
government sought financial help from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and adopted its policy of high interest rates in order
to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
The general lending rate was as high as 20 percent while fixed
deposit rates ranged between 10 percent and 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the rate paid on ordinary savings remained at 5 percent,
the level it had stayed at for about a decade.
</P>
<P>
A year ago, the government reversed its interest rate policy
and lending rates rapidly declined to 9-10 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-deposit rates fell to 5 percent, the lowest level in
decades. And at the beginning of this year, the rate on ordinary
savings was reduced to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Somruk Permkamlangmuang, a 62-year-old pensioner, said people
like him relied heavily on interest income. He said he was worried
by the trend as he cannot afford to risk his money in shares or
other forms of investment.
</P>
<P>
Ammar Siamwalla, a senior economist at the Thailand Development
Research Institute, criticized the banks for punishing their good
customers by charging them higher rates as a means of subsidizing
non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
He urged the banking authorities to force banks to raise
sufficient equity capital from the market to meet loan-loss
provision requirements and cease passing the burden to their good
customers.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans, accounting for 47 percent of the total
outstanding loans of the banks in Thailand, have been a heavy
burden on the banking system.
</P>
<P>
Despite their earlier efforts of recapitalization, most banks
still face an uphill battle to raise capital necessary to cover
their loan losses.
</P>
<P>
As the target of public anger, banks here argued that while
deposit rates have been fallen to their lowest point in decades,
lending rates have also fallen sharply in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said lower deposit rates means those dependent on
interest income, such as retirees, will have less money to spend
and small depositors also are worse off from sinking rates since
they cannot access alternative investments such as stocks or
bonds.
</P>
<P>
However, for larger depositors, the falling returns available
from bank deposits could encourage investment and spending, which
are crucial for the economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't lower interest rates, the economy won't recover.
But if rates fall too low, then consumption won't increase. The
task is to find a balance between the two," a local banker said.
</P>
<P>
In this case, a further fall of deposit rates is just a matter
of time. Bantoon, who is also president of Thai Farmers Bank,
admitted that he himself wasn't sure how long the freeze of
deposit rates by the four banks would be in place.
</P>
<P>
Now, the only way to get banks out of the dilemma is the
corporate debt restructuring process, whose acceleration,
according to Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda, would help
improve the financial system, leading to a more appropriate and
balanced interest rate structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Banks' Rates Policy Arouses Criticism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Bankers' Association
announced Friday that Thailand's four biggest commercial banks
have agreed to maintain their deposit rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Bantoon Lamsam, chairman of the association, announced the
decision on the association's interest rates direction at a press
conference Friday, saying the four major banks, namely Bangkok
Bank, Krung Thai Bank, Siam Commercial Bank and Thai Farmers Bank,
agreed to the freeze.
</P>
<P>
The move is believed to be a compromise made by the banks under
mounting criticism that the industry has enjoyed too wide interest
margins.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, there have been calls among the banking sector
to reduce call savings and time deposit rates, which will be
accompanied by a fall in lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Bankers have said the call savings rate should come down from
about 4.5 percent to around 4 percent before any reduction in
lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Call savings affect millions of savers in the country and
account for the bulk of the banks' funding costs.
</P>
<P>
Time deposit rates have fallen to about the same level as call
savings rates and this is regarded as a major distortion of the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fall in the savings and deposit rates, the prime
lending rate is still kept high, ranging from 9 percent for some
big banks to 11.25 percent for others.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Thai Danu Bank took the lead by cutting
savings and deposit rates to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai Danu's move, accompanied by the anticipation of similar
actions by other commercial banks, has aroused deep concern among
ordinary savers and sparked strong criticism from experts.
</P>
<P>
The Law Society of Thailand had condemned commercial banks for
taking advantage of the public, a view shared by many bank
customers.
</P>
<P>
Many customers said banks are exploiting the public for cutting
deposit rates while keeping lending rates at "high" levels.
</P>
<P>
Bank clients said it is unfair for banks to ask customers to
make sacrifices to help banks obtain funds more cheaply, as
financial institutions created their own problems in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
Customers wondered if banks were colluding to cut deposit rates
and complained that there were few secure options available for
the ordinary savers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
