<DOCNO> XIE19990522.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Political Stability Expected in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali Congress' clear
victory in the parliamentary elections indicates that the
much-awaited political stability will come for the Himalayan
kingdom, analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
The party repeated its feat in the general elections in May
1991 by securing a majority of 106 of the 196 declared seats in
the 205-member House of Representatives. The difference is that
this time political stability may set in for a longer period of
time.
</P>
<P>
First, the party looks more united than ever before. It may be
recalled that in the past years the party was almost split due to
differences between Party President and Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala and Krishna Prasad Bhattarai, another senior leader
of the party.
</P>
<P>
But Koirala held out the olive branch months before the
elections by offering the post-polls premiership to Bhattarai.
Truce between the two septuagenarian leaders undoubtedly
contributed to the party's good showing in the polls held on May 3
and May 17.
</P>
<P>
As the party is all set to form the next government, Koirala
reiterated Thursday that Bhattarai will be the new prime minister.
"I'm committed that the new prime minister should be Krishna
Prasad Bhattarai," he told the press. "I'll not go back on my
promise."
</P>
<P>
He said that as party president, he would extend every
cooperation to the prime minister. "In the future, you'll never
hear dissension in our party."
</P>
<P>
Second, the Nepali Congress would undoubtedly draw lessons from
the past. In the general elections in May 1991, the first in the
kingdom after the multi-party parliamentary system was restored in
1990, the party won a clear majority of 110 seats with three
elected independents joining in later.
</P>
<P>
However, the majority government led by Girija Prasad Koirala
could not complete its five-year term. It collapsed three years
later due to internal dissension.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-term polls in November 1994, the party was reduced
to second position in the parliament as some candidates rebelled.
</P>
<P>
Third, the Nepali Congress won a majority in the house not
because of its performance but due to the split of its arch rival
the Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML).
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the Nepali Congress had not done much to win the
voters' support, but it just benefited from the split of the
CPN-UML, which might otherwise have secured a majority in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Nepalese people are tired of the political
instability in the past four and half years which has seriously
hurt the country's development. The hung parliament produced in
the 1994 mid-term polls gave rise to six governments. Further
instability, needless to say, would be unpopular among the people.
</P>
<P>
There is every reason to believe that the Nepali Congress would
try to behave itself this time for the sake of itself as well as
the nation and the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
