<HEADLINE> Vietnam Reorganizes Private Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has stopped
issuing licenses for new private universities and colleges as a
first step to reorganize the private education sector, Vietnam's
English daily Vietnam News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sector's emergence over the last five years has brought
about positive changes in meeting the needs of urban students, but
a lack of guidelines on its operation has generated several
problems, said Vietnam News.
</P>
<P>
One major problem is that the proliferation of private
universities and colleges is far exceeding actual demand with many
providing very low-quality education.
</P>
<P>
Since the Vietnamese government approved the founding of
private educational institutions in 1994, as many as 14
universities have been established, most of them in Hanoi and Ho
Chi Minh City. These universities and colleges have 65,400
students.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted a lecturer at the Ho Chi Minh City Public
University of Technology as saying private universities and
colleges have increased the size and diversity of their courses
five or six times, especially in foreign languages, business
management and informatics.
</P>
<P>
Apart from stopping licensing of new private universities and
colleges, all students wanting to study at these schools now will
be required to sit for entrance examinations, said an official of
the ministry's department of higher education.
</P>
<P>
The state and relevant ministries will intensify measures to
manage and supervise operations of the private institutions and
improve the quality of training offered by them, added the
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
