<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Surplus Falls 8.9 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government reported a
surplus of 113.5 billion U.S. dollars last month, 8.9 percent
lower than the 124.6-billion-dollar one posted in April 1998, the
Treasury Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
April is the month that people face the deadline to pay their
income taxes. In 1997 and 1998, record surpluses for April
provided lawmakers with an unexpected windfall.
</P>
<P>
The April surplus helped congressional and White House
negotiators reach agreement in 1997 on a five-year plan to balance
the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the lack of an April surprise this year, the
Clinton administration and congressional accountants are still
predicting a bigger surplus, between 79 billion and 111 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We are on track to reach the largest annual budget surplus
ever," said President Clinton in a statement. But he added, "
Despite the good news, this is not a time for complacency."
</P>
<P>
One reason for the lower April surplus this year, as compared
to last April, was a nearly 59 percent increase in tax refunds, to
36.6 billion dollars. That reflects the new 400 dollars per child
credit and new credits for higher education as well as the
increasing popularity of electronic filing and direct deposit,
which offer speedier refunds than paper tax returns and paper
checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
