<HEADLINE> Brazilian Minister Proposes to Shoot Down Drug-Trafficking Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Justice Minister Renan Calheiros
said Friday that he favors shooting down aircraft that invaded the
Brazilian air space with "clearly illicit intentions" of drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking is a transnational crime that permeates
borders, "and I advise to down aircraft that invade the Brazilian
air space with clearly illicit intentions, and I advocate
rewarding denouncers, pardoning or reducing their penalties,"
Calheiros said.
</P>
<P>
The minister asked the congress to reward denouncers, imprison
drug traffickers for life and penally discriminate between
producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the legislators to modify the penitentiary
system, "to prevent simple consumers from coexisting in the
prisons with dangerous drug traffickers," and to permit the
elimination of the bank secret in the case of suspicious persons.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the Brazilian Information Center on Psychotropic Drugs,
Calheiros noted that 20,000 people died in Brazil in 1997 as
victims of chemical dependency, including cases of overdoses,
suicides and assassinations.
</P>
<P>
The minister also briefed the congress on the latest drug
seizure development, saying that the federal police have seized
two tons of cocaine so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the federal police have captured 95 tons of
marihuana, two tons of LSD, and some hashish and heroin. Drug
traffickers detained since 1998 reached 22,000.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the federal police this year will increase from
74 million dollars in 1998 to 81 million, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
