<HEADLINE> Brazil Stocks Close Down Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Brazil's Sao Paulo
exchange, the largest in Latin America, closed down sharply Friday
with the benchmark Bovesa index reducing by 2.98 percent to 11,727
points, against 12,088 points on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was some 384 million U.S. dollars against 433
million dollars on the previous day.
</P>
<P>
In Rio de Janeiro, the stocks also closed down 2.3 percent on
Friday, at 40,650 points against 41,640 points on the previous day.
The volume traded in Rio was some 8.64 million U.S. dollars
against 10 million dollars on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the sharp decline of the Brazil stocks was caused
by the rumor that Argentina's currency, the peso, would be
devaluated, which could damage Brazil's economic recovery and the
bilateral trade between Brazil and Argentina. 
</P>
