<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Disease, Pests Plaguing Forests in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Warm temperatures and drought are
being blamed for the plant disease and insect pests that have been
plaguing 200,000 hectares of trees in central China's Hunan
Province for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The affected area is expected to rise to 267,000 hectares in
June, tripling that of the same period last year, according to
Zhang Jian, director of the Forestry Protection Dvision of the
Hunan Provincial Forestry Department.
</P>
<P>
Many months of warm temperatures have provided favorable
conditions for the growth of insect pests, and the drought that
hit some parts of the province earlier this year has exacerbated
the problem, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
A great number of trees throughout Hunan have been affected by
pine-needle brown-spot and caterpillar diseases, and trees in
Dongkou and Jingzhou counties in southwestern Hunan have been
killed by these diseases and insects.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has issued a circular calling for
effective measures to fight against the plant disease and pests,
and airplanes will be used to spray pesticide in the cities of
Chenzhou, Yongzhou, Changde, and Shaoyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
