<HEADLINE> Abadjiev Receives Honorary Doctorate from Sports Academy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Ivan Abadjiev, the most successful
weightlifting coach of Bulgaria, was awarded an honorary doctor's
degree by the National Sports Academy on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a well-deserved recognition for Abadjiev's
contribution to Bulgarian sport," said Prof. Georgi Kabourov, the
Academy's Rector.
</P>
<P>
Talking to a capacity audience, Abadjiev expounded his
methodology which earned  Bulgarian weightlifters world fame, and
thanked for the high honour.
</P>
<P>
Abadjiev, 67 was a national weightlifter from 1951 to 1960 in
the Sports Academy (then known as the Higher Institute of Physical
Culture).
</P>
<P>
He took silver in the Tehran World Championships in 1957. He
became the coach of the national team in 1969, but was dismissed
in 1989. He made a living by doing odd jobs as a badminton coach,
locksmith and installer being reinstated in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Abadjiev has been the coach of 10 Olympic champions, 65 world
championships winners and 70 European championships gold medalists.
More than 200 world records have been broken under him.
</P>
<P>
"All of my successes belong to Bulgaria because I am Bulgarian.
This is where I was born, studied and became what I am now. The
honorary doctor's degree gives me a fresh impetus to work to the
last for the victories of Bulgarian weightlifting," Abadjiev said.
</P>
<P>
Abadjiev is the ninth honorary doctor of the Sports Academy and
the first alumnus to have received the degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
