<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT0045, May 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Friday threatened foreign
diplomats in Yugoslavia, saying that those diplomats should know
it's dangerous for them to stay in Belgrade as the U.S.-led NATO
continues its air campaign.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin suggested all the other
countries should pull out their diplomats from Belgrade as the
United States did. (US-Kosovo-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Russia, Switzerland and Greece have decided
to set up "FOCUS" Project to combine their efforts on the delivery
and distribution of emergency humanitarian assistance on the
territory of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY), a press
release from the Russian Mission to the United Nations said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The press release, being distributed here, said that the three
countries made the decision "with the view to providing
humanitarian assistance to the affected population of FRY."
</P>
<P>
On April 28, the Steering Group on humanitarian response was
set up to carry out the project. (UN-Kosovo-Project)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday signed a 15
billion U.S. dollars spending bill to fund the bombing of
Yugoslavia, boost U.S. military readiness and fund other programs.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton had put his
signature to the legislation, to which Congress gave final
approval on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate Thursday approved the measure on a vote of 64-
36. The House approved the compromise measure Tuesday. (Clinton-
Kosovo-Funding)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Friday named six
members of the new cabinet under Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, 47, was confirmed Wednesday as premier by the State
Duma, or lower house of parliament, to replace Yevgeny Primakov,
who was sacked a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
Former Railways Minister Nikolai Aksenenko was named first
deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Other deputy prime ministers are expected to be appointed next
week, the Itar-Tass news agency reported, quoting a government
source  (Russia-Cabinet-Members)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- Six persons were killed and 40 others were injured,
with 10 of them critically, when a passenger bus collided head-on
with a truck on Dhaka-Khulna highway Friday afternoon, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The passenger bus from western Bangladesh's Faridpur district,
which was heading toward Magura, some 110 kilometers southwest of
here, collided with a loaded truck coming from the opposite
direction, and the badly damaged truck fell into the roadside
ditch, the reports said. (Bangladesh-Road Accident) 
</P>
</TEXT>
