<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil To Develop Tourism in Southern States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government has
decided to develop tourism in its southern states, Sports and
Tourism Minister Rafael Greca said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Greca said the federal and state governments, and the
Interamerican Development Bank will invest 1.5 million dollars to
develop tourism in the states of Rio Grande do Sul, Parana, Santa
Catarina and Mato Grosso do Sul.
</P>
<P>
The idea is to recover tourism industry in the southern region,
mainly in the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) region, where
privileged beaches, El Pantanal (marshlands) and the Foz de Iguazu
waterfalls are located, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The south of the country is very beautiful and needs more
investments to better exploit local tourism, which has much to
offer," Greca said.
</P>
<P>
Four million foreign tourists visited Brazil last year, who
provided 3.6 billion dollars in hard currency for the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
