<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese and Dannish Players Dominate Men's Singles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Dannish and Chinese shuttlers
have displayed their power in the men's singles event by sharing
the semi-final berths at the World Badminton Championships.
</P>
<P>
After the quarter-finals Friday evening, Dannish shuttlers
secured two medals of the championships through world number one
Peter Gade Christensen and Olympic gold medal winner Poul-erik
Hoyer Larsen while Sun Jun of China and Fung Permadi of Chinese
Taipei shared the other two places.
</P>
<P>
Gade, a top favourite for the gold, defeated his teammate
defending champion Peter Rasmussen 15-3, 15-13 and Larsen roared
from first set down to beat H. Hendrawan of Indonesia 8-15, 15-4,
15-4.
</P>
<P>
However, another Dannish did not have such fortune when Kenneth
Jonassen, who made his debut top eight places at world
championships, lost Fung Permadi of Chinese Taipei 15-13, 12-15
and 15-10.
</P>
<P>
"Jonasson did not have patience in the last set," said Permadi,
who formerly a famous Indonesian shuttler.
</P>
<P>
China's Sun Jun, runner-up at the 1997 world championships in
Glasgow, overplayed another Dannish Thomas Stuer-Laudridsen in the
quarter-final, winning the match at 15-5, 15-13.
</P>
<P>
When leading the second set at 13-9, Sun Jun slowed down his
pace which allowed experienced Stuer-Laudridsen to trail the score
to 13-all.
</P>
<P>
At the crucial moment, Sun Jun managed to find back his form
and took the match with two points in a run.
</P>
<P>
Despite the victory, Sun Jun was in no way satisfied with his
performance. "I could not concentrate in the second set in which I
could not attack at the net," he said. "I am lucky to win as he
had too many errors in the match," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals on Saturday, Sun Jun will meet Stuer-
Laudridsen and Gade faces Permadi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
