<HEADLINE> South Korea and England to Vie for Mixed Double Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korean and English
shuttlers will vie for the title of the mixed doubles event after
they scored respective victory in the semi-finals of the World
Badminton Championships on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Top seeds Kim Dong Monn and Ra Kyung Min of South Korea edged
defending champions Liu Yong and Ge Fei of China 15-7, 7-15, 15-8
while second seeded Simon Archer and Joanne Goode trounced Michael
Sogaard and Rikke Olsen of Denmark 15-5 and 15-9 for the final.
</P>
<P>
The final showdown is a repetition of that at the All England
Open Championships two months ago when the English duo defeated
the South Korean counterparts for the crown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, top seeds Huang Nanyan and Yang Wei of China lost to
Ra Kyung Min and Chung Jae Hee of South Korea in the women's
doubles after winning the close match at 15-5, 12-15 and 13-15 in
102 minutes, the longest clash in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean duo will take on Dannish pair Ann Jorgensen
and Majken Vange in a semi-final on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jorgensen and Vange claimed the spot in top four by defeating
Joanne Goode and Donna Kellogg of England 15-17, 15-10 and 15-13
in a quarter-final.
</P>
<P>
Another semi-final showdown of the event will be held between
two Chinese pairs with second seeds Ge Fei and Gu Jun taking on
Qin Yiyuan and Gao Ling.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia suffered a big setback in men's doubles when three
pairs from the country were eliminated after the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
The semi-final match in the event will take Simon Archer/Nathan
Robertson of England against Lee Dong Soo/Yoo Yong Chung of South
Korea, Ha Tae Kwon/Kim Dong Moon, also from South Korea against
Chinese duo Zhang Jun/Zhang Wei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
